{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608961"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16055"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16055"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.17,0.74,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63713"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16055"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63713"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERoutine antenatal care requires regular monitoring throughout pregnancy, with visit frequency increasing as the pregnancy progresses. The schedule of visits is designed to optimally detect and prevent complications while avoiding unnecessary interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the recommended frequency of routine antenatal visits after 36 weeks gestation in an uncomplicated pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Every 4-6 weeks","Every 2-3 weeks","Weekly","Every 3 days","Every day"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn uncomplicated pregnancies, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweekly\u003C/strong\u003E visits are recommended after 36 weeks gestation. This schedule allows for appropriate monitoring of maternal and fetal wellbeing during the final weeks of pregnancy when various complications become more common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 4-6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is too infrequent for late pregnancy - this schedule is appropriate for the second trimester\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 2-3 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the typical frequency between 28-36 weeks but is insufficient for term pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 3 days\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily frequent for uncomplicated pregnancies and create undue burden\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery day\u003C/strong\u003E visits would be excessive and are only indicated in specific high-risk situations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWeekly visits allow practitioners to monitor blood pressure, fetal growth, and position while discussing common concerns and birth preparation. More frequent visits may be required if complications develop.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Antenatal visits should occur weekly after 36 weeks gestation in uncomplicated pregnancies","More frequent monitoring is required in late pregnancy to detect complications like pre-eclampsia and fetal growth concerns"],"references":["Catling CJ, Medley N, Foureur M, Ryan C, Leap N, Teate A, Homer CS. Group versus conventional antenatal care for women. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Feb 4;2015(2):CD007622. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD007622.pub3. PMID: 25922865; PMCID: PMC6465187.","Government of Western Australian. Antenatal care schedule. wa.gov.au Available from: https://www.kemh.health.wa.gov.au/~/media/HSPs/NMHS/Hospitals/WNHS/Documents/Clinical-guidelines/Obs-Gyn-Guidelines/Antenatal-Care-Schedule.pdf?thn=0","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16055"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T12:04:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T12:04:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8746"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63713"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":